05146nam a22006855i 9780520973053DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1328938530  a97805209730537 a10.1525/97805209730532doi  a(DE-B1597)534796  a(OCoLC)1078953805  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aU21.5b.B489 2019 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a355.02/130956942231 aBen-Eliezer, Uri, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar over Peace :bOne Hundred Years of Israel's Militaristic Nationalism /cUri Ben-Eliezer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Militaristic Nationalism and War -- t2. The Birth of Militaristic Nationalism in Pre-state Israel -- t3. The Establishment of a Dominant Nation-State: The 1948 War of Independence -- t4. A Nation-in-Arms: The Sinai War of 1956 -- t5. Militaristic Nationalism and Occupation: The Six-Day War of 1967 -- t6. The Price: The Yom Kippur War of 1973 -- t7. The Decline of the Nation-in-Arms: The 1982 Lebanon War -- t8. The Emergence of Liberal Nationalism: From the First Intifada to the 1993 Oslo Accords -- t9. The Return of Militaristic Nationalism: The 2000–2005 Al-Aqsa Intifada -- t10. Religious and Militaristic Nationalism: Israel’s New Wars -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aViolence and war have raged between Zionists and Palestinians for over a century, ever since Zionists, trying to establish a nation-state in Palestine, were forced to confront the fact that the country was already populated. Covering every conflict in Israel’s history, War over Peace reveals that Israeli nationalism was born ethnic and militaristic and has embraced these characteristics to this day. In his sweeping and original synthesis, Uri Ben-Eliezer shows that this militaristic nationalism systematically drives Israel to find military solutions for its national problems, based on the idea that the homeland is sacred and the territory is indivisible. When Israelis opposed to this ideology brought about change during a period that led to the Oslo Accords in the 1990s, cultural and political forces, reinforced by religious and messianic elements, prevented the implementation of the agreements, which brought violence back in the form of new wars. War over Peace is essential reading for anyone who wants to understand the role of ethnic nationalism and militarism in Israel as well as throughout the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitarismzIsraelxHistory. 0aNationalismzIsraelxHistory. 0aPolitics and warzIsraelxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCA Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065207908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520973053?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520973053423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com